open-bastion (0.1.5) unstable; urgency=medium

  * SSH key fingerprint binding on /pam/authorize and /pam/verify
    (requires LemonLDAP::NG PamAccess >= 0.1.16 and SSHCA >= 0.1.16).
    pam_openbastion now forwards the SHA256 fingerprint of the SSH
    key used to open the session; LLNG cross-checks it against the
    user's persistent session (_sshCerts) and rejects the call if the
    certificate is unknown, revoked, or expired. Closes the gap where
    a cert revoked on the portal could still open a session or
    escalate via sudo until the KRL propagated (or at all if
    RevokedKeys was missing from sshd_config).
  * New helper /usr/local/sbin/ob-ssh-principals, installed by
    ob-bastion-setup and ob-backend-setup as AuthorizedPrincipalsCommand
    "%u %f". It atomically drops the fingerprint to
    /run/open-bastion/ssh-fp/<sshd-session-pid>.fp (mktemp + mv).
    pam_openbastion walks /proc up to the sshd-session ancestor and
    reads the file, validating owner/mode/nlink/size/format. A
    systemd-tmpfiles drop-in recreates the spool directory at boot.
  * Spool directory hardened: owned by the
    AuthorizedPrincipalsCommandUser (typically "nobody") with mode
    0700, so no other local user can pre-create or substitute a drop
    file. pam_openbastion refuses the spool if the directory is group/
    world-writable, and rejects any drop file whose owner/mode/nlink
    does not match (0600, nlink==1, uid == dir uid).
  * Strict SHA256 filter: pam_openbastion only forwards fingerprints
    matching SHA256:<base64>. Prevents systematic HTTP 400 when sshd
    is configured with "FingerprintHash md5".
  * Integration tests: fingerprint match/unknown/malformed on
    /pam/authorize, revocation via /ssh/myrevoke without KRL refresh,
    and end-to-end SSH attempt refused at PAM account phase.
  * Re-run ob-bastion-setup / ob-backend-setup after upgrade to pick
    up the new AuthorizedPrincipalsCommand line and install the spool
    helper.

 -- Xavier Guimard <xguimard@linagora.com>  Mon, 20 Apr 2026 07:00:00 +0200

open-bastion (0.1.4) unstable; urgency=medium

  * NSS config path fix: libnss_openbastion now reads its config from
    /etc/open-bastion/nss_openbastion.conf (the location where CMake
    installs it and where ob-bastion-setup/ob-backend-setup have always
    written). Previously hard-coded to /etc/nss_llng.conf (leftover from
    llng-pam-module rename), so NSS silently refused to resolve users.
    Re-run ob-bastion-setup or ob-backend-setup after upgrade.
  * Session recorder wrapper (ob-session-recorder-wrapper): hardened
    against privilege escalation. Explicitly drop elevated gid via
    setregid() before exec; create session dir with mode 2770 (setgid)
    so files inherit the ob-sessions group without the script needing
    elevated gid; strip dangerous env vars (LD_*, BASH_ENV, ENV,
    SHELLOPTS, BASHOPTS, CDPATH, GCONV_PATH, NLSPATH, TMPDIR, ...);
    harden PATH; validate username against ^[a-z_][a-z0-9_.-]*$;
    resolve username via getpwuid() instead of env.
  * ob-session-recorder: derive SESSION_USER from "id -un" instead of
    the user-controllable $USER env var; validate with same regex.
  * Session directory creation: TOCTOU races fixed (use fstat/fchown/
    fchmod on fd rather than path).
  * Defense-in-depth sudo: new system group open-bastion-sudo created
    by postinst/spec; pam_openbastion session hook syncs membership on
    each login based on sudo_allowed from /pam/authorize
    (true -> add to group, false -> remove). ob-bastion-setup writes
    /etc/sudoers.d/open-bastion restricting sudo to %open-bastion-sudo
    (existing files are not overwritten). nscd cache invalidated after
    membership change so sudo sees the update immediately.
  * NSS config and token files now opened with O_NOFOLLOW and verified
    via fstat: must be owned by root, must be a regular file, must not
    be group/world-writable; token file must not be group/world-readable.
  * NSS write_callback: integer overflow check and 256 KB response size
    cap to prevent memory exhaustion.
  * NSS module: added syslog diagnostics for silent rejection paths.
  * Docker demos: removed the "useradd -m" fallback that masked NSS
    failures; demos now fail fast when NSS cannot resolve users.
  * New quick-start/ directory: minimal 2-container demo using
    yadd/lemonldap-ng-portal directly with the plugin autoloader (no
    customPlugins edit), with README covering installation of
    Open-Bastion plugins on an existing LLNG via lemonldap-ng-store or
    Debian packages.

 -- Xavier Guimard <xguimard@linagora.com>  Sat, 18 Apr 2026 23:00:00 +0200

open-bastion (0.1.3) unstable; urgency=medium

  * Mode E hardening: tested end-to-end deployment
  * Fix PAM module name: pam_llng.so -> pam_openbastion.so
  * Fix NSS module symbols: _nss_llng_* -> _nss_openbastion_*
  * Fix NSS config: nsswitch.conf uses 'openbastion', server_token_file key
  * Fix ob-enroll: send client_secret to device endpoint (optional)
  * Fix ob-bastion-setup: add Include directive, AuthorizedPrincipalsCommand,
    PermitRootLogin no, NSS configuration, pam_mkhomedir.so
  * Fix session recorder paths: ob-session-recorder, /etc/open-bastion/
  * Fix sudo Mode E: remove pam_unix.so from account (NSS-only users),
    create /etc/sudoers.d/open-bastion
  * Session recording privilege separation via setgid wrapper
    (ob-session-recorder-wrapper, group ob-sessions, mode 1770)
  * New risk R-S18: session recording tampering (mitigated P=1/I=1)
  * Pre-hardening bootstrap: securetty ttyS0, PermitRootLogin no,
    service account for emergency access

